gland":"Derbyshire, England, United Kingdom","Wirksworth, Derbyshire, England":"Wirksworth, Derbyshire, England","Hopton, Derbyshire, England":"Hopton, Derbyshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"GYLES","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: variant of   Giles  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Giles","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): from a medieval personal name, Middle English <i>Giles</i> or <i>Gile</i>, a borrowing from Old French <i>Gil(l)e(s)</i>. This is from Latin <i>Aegidius</i> and this presumably from Greek <i>aigidion</i> ‘kid, young goat’ (alternatively, it could be a Late Latin formation from the Latin personal name <i>Eggius</i> + the suffix <i>-idius</i>). The personal name was widely used in France and the Low Countries, partly through veneration of Saint Gilles de Provence, supposedly a hermit of the 7th century near Arles; he was patron saint of cripples, hence the dedication of Saint Giles Cripplegate in London, though the personal name itself was less common in England than elsewhere in Europe. See also   Gilles  .","Irish: adopted as an Anglicized equivalent of Gaelic <b>Ó Glaisne</b>, a County Louth name based on <i>glas</i> ‘green, blue, gray’.","French: variant of   Gilles  , a cognate of 1 above."]}]},{"name":"Ralph","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From a Norman French name, <i>Raulf</i>, a contracted form of the Germanic personal name <i>Radulf</i>, derived from <i>rād</i> ‘counsel’ + <i>wulf</i> ‘wolf’. The spelling with <i>-ph</i> is due to classical influence in the 18th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Ralf","meanings":["From a Norman French name, <i>Raulf</i>, a contracted form of the Germanic personal name <i>Radulf</i>, derived from <i>rād</i> ‘counsel’ + <i>wulf</i> ‘wolf’. The spelling with <i>-ph</i> is due to classical influence in the 18th century."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":2,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705197,"age":75,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Ralph GYLES II was born about 1380, in Wirksworth, Derbyshire, England, his father, Robert GYLES I, was 32 and his mother, Mrs. Robert Gell, was 32. He married Mrs. Ralph Gell about 1400, in Wirksworth, Derbyshire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son."},"et":{"about 1380–":"umbes 1380–Surnud","1380–Male":"1380–Surnud","1380–Female":"1380–Surnud","1410–1471":"1410–1471","1350–1408":"1350–1408","1350–Female":"1350–Surnud","about 1370":"umbes 1370","about 1380":"umbes 1380","1455":"1455","1410":"1410","about 1400":"umbes 1400","1350":"1350","1471":"1471","about 1410":"umbes 1410","1382":"1382","1408":"1408","1380":"1380","Derbyshire, England":"Derbyshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Wirksworth, Derbyshire, England":"Wirksworth, Derbyshire, England","Hopton, Derbyshire, England":"Hopton, Derbyshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1380–":"noin 1380–Kuollut","1380–Male":"1380–Kuollut","1380–Female":"1380–Kuollut","1410–1471":"1410–1471","1